{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502735"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1894"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1894"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.02,0.05,0.43,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82998"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1894"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68058"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"813"},{"type":"tags","id":"4267"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28394"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82998"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a small nodule on his right hand which has been present for about two weeks. He has had no recent trauma to the area and no abnormal sensation or motor function. He is worried that it might be cancer. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. He smokes 15 cigarettes and consumes two standard drinks per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has full range of motion in his wrist and hand joints and there is no tenderness on palpation. The lump is hard and nodular and clearly visible on the palmar aspect of his right hand (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Giant cell tumour of tendon sheath","Raynaud\u0027s disease","Trigger finger","Ganglion cyst","Dupuytren\u0027s contracture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of the early phase of \u003Cstrong\u003EDupuytren\u0027s contracture\u003C/strong\u003E where there is nodule formation in the palmar fascia. Another feature is the blanching on the palmar aspect, occurring when the fingers are extended. This condition typically progresses from nodules to pitting to cords and finally to contracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell tumour of tendon sheath\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign tumour that typically presents as a firm, non-tender nodule on the fingers or hand, but it is less common than Dupuytren\u0027s contracture and usually not located on the palmar fascia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaynaud\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E results in decreased blood supply to the fingers and can present as numbness in the fingertips accompanied with colour changes as the external environment\u0027s temperature fluctuates. It may be a symptom of autoimmune diseases such as systemic lupus erythematosus or scleroderma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrigger finger\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as stenosing tenosynovitis, will present with a flexed finger or thumb due to mechanical inhibition at the A1 pulley.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGanglion cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a fluid-filled cyst that typically presents in the hands or wrist. It tends to be firm and freely mobile.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dupuytren\u0027s contracture is a slowly progressive condition affecting the palmar fascia, leading to nodules and potential contractures.","Treatment for Dupuytren\u0027s contracture varies based on severity, ranging from observation to surgical intervention.","Early identification of Dupuytren\u0027s contracture can help in monitoring and managing progression."],"references":["Currie KB, Tadisina KK, Mackinnon SE. Common Hand Conditions: A Review. JAMA. 2022 Jun 28;327(24):2434-2445. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.8481. Erratum in: JAMA. 2023 Aug 22;330(8):772. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.14783. PMID: 35762992. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35762992/","Rea, Paul (2016-01-01), Rea, Paul (ed.), \u0022Chapter 3 - Neck\u0022, Essential Clinically Applied Anatomy of the Peripheral Nervous System in the Head and Neck, Academic Press, pp. 131\u2013183, doi:10.1016/b978-0-12-803633-4.00003-x, ISBN 978-0-12-803633-4, retrieved 2020-10-25","Ruettermann M, Hermann RM, Khatib-Chahidi K, Werker PMN. Dupuytren\u0027s Disease-Etiology and Treatment. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2021 Nov 19;118(46):781-788. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.m2021.0325. PMID: 34702442; PMCID: PMC8864671. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34702442/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1894"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20394"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20394"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Yu75L89pOJc9F1TYruEi1n58cLWx8V.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Yu75L89pOJc9F1TYruEi1n58cLWx8V.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68058"},